Section 1.2.  Basic use case for SCHC as an Ethertype
================================================================================

REQUIRED FOR CONCEPTUAL ALIGNMENT. The draft's "the SCHC session (called
instance)" fuses two concepts that -06 keeps distinct. The fusion is locally
true of the LoRa topology being described, because preconfiguration of a
single MAC peer pair forces a one-to-one correspondence, and it fails at the
very point the draft extends the argument to Ethernet. The paragraph is
rewritten rather than substituted. Note also that "MAC-Layer endpoints"
denotes link-layer peers, NOT -06 Endpoints, and must not be translated;
"more powerful endpoint", two sentences later, does denote an -06 Endpoint.

-  In the case of a classical LPWAN link such as LoRa [RFC9011], the use
-  of SCHC to compress the transported protocol, as well as the SCHC
-  session (called instance) to use, are implicit.  The MAC-Layer
-  endpoints are preconfigured so there can be only one session, and
-  there can be only SCHC.  When extended to Ethernet and more powerful
-  endpoint, this model is way too restrictive, and it is necessary to
-  signal both the use of SCHC and the SCHC session to be used.  While
-  the SCHC WG is charterd to produce the latter, the Ethertype defined
-  in this document will be used to signal SCHC as the upper* layer
-  protocol.
+  In the case of a classical LPWAN link such as LoRa [RFC9011], both the
+  use of SCHC to compress the transported protocol and the selection of
+  the SCHC Instance and Session that apply are implicit.  The MAC-layer
+  peers are preconfigured, so a single Instance and a single Session
+  exist on the link, and SCHC is the only upper-layer protocol carried;
+  the Discriminator is supplied entirely by the link layer.  When SCHC is
+  extended to Ethernet and to more capable Endpoints, this model is way
+  too restrictive: an Endpoint may host several Instances and take part
+  in several Sessions, so it is necessary to signal both the use of SCHC
+  and the information that the Dispatcher needs in order to select the
+  Instance and the Session.  While the SCHC WG is chartered to produce
+  the latter, the Ethertype defined in this document supplies the former:
+  it is the Discriminator that signals SCHC as the upper-layer protocol.

  (Rationale: -06 Section 3 defines Instance as "a logical component of an
  Endpoint that executes the actual SCHC operations" and Session as "a
  communication session between two or more Instances that share a common
  Context". -06 Appendix A.2.1 Tables 1 and 2 show that the two need not
  correspond one-to-one: a gateway may hold one Instance serving many
  Sessions, or one Instance per Session. Appendix A.2.1 also confirms the
  link-layer reading of the LoRa case, treating the DevEUI as the source of
  a Discriminator rather than as an Endpoint.

  What the paragraph asserts changes: it no longer says that "session" and
  "instance" are the same thing. What any implementation does does not
  change, and the division of labour the draft draws -- Ethertype signals
  SCHC, SCHC WG signals the rest -- is preserved exactly.)

